WEBVTT

00:03.128 --> 00:04.713
OTTO: We are
going into hiding.

00:04.713 --> 00:06.924
When we get there, we need your
help getting food and medicine.

00:06.924 --> 00:08.217
MIEP: Whatever you need.

00:08.217 --> 00:09.676
There was a
roundup last night.

00:09.676 --> 00:13.096
German soldiers blocked off
an entire neighborhood and

00:13.096 --> 00:15.349
arrested all the Jews.

00:15.349 --> 00:16.934
FRITZ: Can you help me, then?

00:16.934 --> 00:19.353
Can you find me
a place to hide?

00:19.353 --> 00:22.231
MIEP: I found a place,
a hiding place.

00:22.231 --> 00:23.815
FRITZ: Mr. Frank!

00:23.815 --> 00:25.651
I thought you
were in Switzerland.

00:25.651 --> 00:26.777
OTTO: Welcome to Switzerland.

00:26.777 --> 00:29.404
(laughter, chatter)

00:29.404 --> 00:32.699
BRAM: There are a number of
us here who disagree with

00:32.699 --> 00:34.743
the policies of the occupiers.

00:34.743 --> 00:35.869
We'd like you to join us.

00:35.869 --> 00:37.329
JAN: Yes.
Yes, yes.

00:37.329 --> 00:38.914
I'd love to help.

00:38.914 --> 00:40.958
MIEP: My mom, my mother had
no husband and she was poor.

00:40.958 --> 00:43.544
She found a Dutch family who
were willing to adopt me,

00:43.544 --> 00:45.963
and I repay her by what,
forgetting her?

00:45.963 --> 00:48.966
OTTO: It doesn't seem to me
that you've forgotten her.

00:50.133 --> 00:51.426
SS OFFICER: Do you
know these children?

00:51.426 --> 00:52.594
JAN: Yes.

00:52.594 --> 00:54.179
We're their
grandmother's tenants.

00:54.179 --> 00:56.181
SS OFFICER: Their parents were
arrested at the train station.

00:56.181 --> 00:57.808
MIEP: Alfred,
Liddy, come here.

00:57.808 --> 00:59.810
SS OFFICER: They'd better
not be here when I come back.

01:15.450 --> 01:21.039
♪ ♪

01:24.167 --> 01:26.044
JAN: You like apples?
You like apples?

01:26.044 --> 01:29.047
LIDDY: Where are you going?
MIEP: To my job.

01:29.715 --> 01:33.260
LIDDY: Where's Jan going?
MIEP: To his job.

01:33.260 --> 01:34.886
LIDDY: You can't
leave us alone here.

01:34.886 --> 01:37.097
MIEP: I'm not going
to leave you alone.

01:37.097 --> 01:39.433
I'm gonna wait until your
grandmother gets back

01:39.433 --> 01:41.727
with your uncle.

01:43.353 --> 01:44.813
LIDDY: What's that
piece of paper for?

01:44.813 --> 01:45.981
MIEP: It's for
blotting my lipstick.

01:45.981 --> 01:47.441
LIDDY: Can I try
your lipstick?

01:47.441 --> 01:48.900
MIEP: No, no.
It's for grown-ups.

01:48.900 --> 01:50.152
JAN: Come on.
MIEP: Sit down.

01:50.152 --> 01:51.278
ALFRED: I don't want porridge.

01:51.278 --> 01:52.821
JAN: Okay.
Um, what about toast?

01:52.821 --> 01:53.989
ALFRED: I don't like toast.

01:53.989 --> 01:55.324
LIDDY: I can do a cartwheel.
Wanna see?

01:55.324 --> 01:56.533
JAN: Um.
MIEP: Uh, maybe later.

01:56.533 --> 01:57.576
ALFRED: I do.

01:57.576 --> 01:59.536
JAN: Oh!
MIEP: Oh. Um, uh.

01:59.536 --> 02:01.580
MAX: So Frannie and Lou were
arrested at the train station
and taken where?

02:01.580 --> 02:02.789
MRS. STOPPELMAN: I don't know.

02:02.789 --> 02:03.915
MAX: Who brought
the kids here?

02:03.915 --> 02:05.375
MRS. STOPPELMAN: Some SS man.

02:05.375 --> 02:06.585
He dropped them off with Miep
and Jan and said they'd

02:06.585 --> 02:08.170
better not be here
when he gets back.

02:08.170 --> 02:10.547
MAX: Liddy, sweetie,
tell Uncle Max exactly what

02:10.547 --> 02:11.757
happened at the train station.

02:11.757 --> 02:13.133
LIDDY: I don't remember.

02:13.133 --> 02:15.218
MAX: Liddy, please.
This is very important.

02:15.218 --> 02:17.721
When the men took your
mum and dad, did they say

02:17.721 --> 02:19.723
where they were going?

02:19.723 --> 02:21.683
LIDDY: I can't remember.
MAX: Liddy.

02:21.683 --> 02:23.477
LIDDY: Alfred doesn't
like his milk cold.

02:23.477 --> 02:24.603
JAN: It's fine he
needs to have something.

02:24.603 --> 02:25.854
Oh!

02:25.854 --> 02:26.897
MAX: Um.
LIDDY: You have to heat it.

02:26.897 --> 02:28.398
MAX: Please,
this is important!

02:28.398 --> 02:29.941
Did they say where
they were going?

02:29.941 --> 02:31.860
LIDDY: I can't remember.
MAX: Liddy, try to remember!

02:34.905 --> 02:36.198
MIEP: Stop!

02:36.198 --> 02:37.282
She doesn't remember what
happened last night,

02:37.282 --> 02:38.909
it's a blessing!
Just let her forget it!

02:38.909 --> 02:40.911
Leave her alone!

02:47.709 --> 02:48.877
I'm sorry.

02:48.877 --> 02:51.296
I'm, I'm sorry.

02:51.296 --> 02:52.589
I know you're worried
about Frannie and Lou,

02:52.589 --> 02:53.840
I, I am as well.

02:53.840 --> 02:55.592
JAN: Max, she worked
at the Jewish Council.

02:55.592 --> 02:57.052
Surely, you can speak to them?

02:57.052 --> 02:58.512
MAX: Yes.

02:58.512 --> 03:01.932
Uh, I can at least try and
find out where they've gone.

03:01.932 --> 03:04.518
LIDDY: Now do you want
to see my cartwheel?

03:04.518 --> 03:06.645
MIEP: I'd love to.

03:06.645 --> 03:08.146
Their kids are gonna have to
be hidden, and they're gonna

03:08.146 --> 03:11.191
ask us to help hide them,
you do know that.

03:11.191 --> 03:12.734
We can't, right?

03:12.734 --> 03:15.654
JAN: Us? No, we can't do it.
I wish we could.

03:15.654 --> 03:16.988
MIEP: Definitely
not in the Annex.

03:16.988 --> 03:18.073
JAN: Yeah.

03:18.073 --> 03:20.075
MIEP: And she's
just our landlady.

03:20.075 --> 03:22.536
JAN: Yeah.
We barely know her.

03:22.536 --> 03:24.204
We're already looking
after loads of people.

03:24.204 --> 03:25.622
MIEP: Yes. Yes.

03:25.622 --> 03:27.749
And taking any more
will put everyone at risk.

03:27.749 --> 03:29.084
JAN: Yeah. Exactly.

03:29.084 --> 03:31.461
MIEP: We can't save everyone.

03:31.461 --> 03:33.672
JAN: No.

03:33.672 --> 03:35.966
MIEP: Why are you
going in so early?

03:35.966 --> 03:38.385
JAN: I've just got to pick up
a few things on the way.

03:38.385 --> 03:41.471
MIEP: No, you just wanna
get away from those kids.

03:41.471 --> 03:43.890
JAN: No, they're
quite sweet, actually.

03:43.890 --> 03:46.143
Liddy follows you
around like your shadow.

03:46.143 --> 03:48.854
You're good with her,
you know.

03:48.854 --> 03:51.523
MIEP: Jan Gies, don't do that.

03:51.523 --> 03:53.358
JAN: Do what?

03:53.358 --> 03:56.445
MIEP: Start hinting about having
children, saying I'm a natural.

03:56.445 --> 03:57.946
JAN: I'm not.

03:57.946 --> 04:00.365
MIEP: I told you when we first
met I don't want children.

04:00.365 --> 04:02.033
If you think I'm gonna wake up
one day and suddenly have

04:02.033 --> 04:03.410
the urge to be a mother.

04:03.410 --> 04:05.245
JAN: I take pity on two
traumatized children that

04:05.245 --> 04:06.997
a Nazi deposits at our door,

04:06.997 --> 04:08.707
and suddenly you
think I want kids?

04:08.707 --> 04:10.375
MIEP: Do you?

04:10.375 --> 04:14.588
JAN: I want to get
a seat on this bus.

04:15.964 --> 04:17.257
I'll see you later.

04:17.257 --> 04:18.258
MIEP: And when they ask?

04:18.258 --> 04:20.010
We're not hiding those kids.

04:20.010 --> 04:22.637
JAN: We can't.
We, we can't. We can't.

04:22.637 --> 04:23.847
MIEP: No.
JAN: No.

04:23.847 --> 04:26.057
MIEP: Okay.
JAN: I'll see you later.

04:26.057 --> 04:28.727
MIEP: Bye.
JAN: Bye.

04:40.697 --> 04:45.619
(unlocking door)

04:46.036 --> 04:47.913
MIEP: Can I help you?

04:47.913 --> 04:50.499
TONNY: No.
I'm waiting for Otto Frank.

04:50.499 --> 04:52.209
MIEP: He's not here.

04:52.209 --> 04:53.960
TONNY: He will be.
We have a standing meeting.

04:53.960 --> 04:55.212
MIEP: Oh.

04:55.212 --> 04:57.631
Uh, he has nothing
in his calendar.

04:58.215 --> 05:00.550
TONNY: Are you the secretary?

05:00.550 --> 05:01.843
Call him.

05:01.843 --> 05:03.512
Tell him Tonny Ahlers
is waiting.

05:03.512 --> 05:06.097
MIEP: Mr. Frank has
moved out of town.

05:06.097 --> 05:08.225
TONNY: What? Where?

05:08.225 --> 05:10.101
MIEP: Switzerland.

05:10.101 --> 05:11.186
TONNY: Give me the address.

05:11.186 --> 05:12.395
MIEP: I don't have it.

05:12.395 --> 05:14.481
TONNY: I don't believe you.

05:14.481 --> 05:16.191
MIEP: He didn't give me one,
I'm sorry.

05:16.191 --> 05:20.570
Sorry I can't be of more help.
Have a good day.

05:29.704 --> 05:35.961
♪ ♪

05:35.961 --> 05:39.548
(chatter)

05:44.761 --> 05:46.680
BRAM: You're a born criminal.

05:46.680 --> 05:48.723
JAN: It was easier than
you made it out to be.

05:48.723 --> 05:49.975
BRAM: Well, keep going.

05:49.975 --> 05:53.019
The Resistance needs all
the ID cards it can get.

05:53.019 --> 05:55.689
Especially those
without a J stamped on them.

05:55.689 --> 05:58.942
You just saved four lives.

06:02.946 --> 06:04.823
What?

06:04.823 --> 06:07.450
JAN: Do you know
anyone hiding children?

06:07.450 --> 06:09.995
Children who are
separated from their parents?

06:09.995 --> 06:11.788
Our landlady has
two grandkids.

06:11.788 --> 06:14.749
BRAM: Wait.
The less I know, the better.

06:23.800 --> 06:26.720
JAN: Here? Really?

06:26.720 --> 06:27.888
MIEP: All right.

06:27.888 --> 06:30.098
We only have 15 minutes
before we open.

06:30.098 --> 06:32.601
Mrs. van Pels, a
book on French cuisine?

06:32.601 --> 06:34.519
PETER: Why?
All we have here is beans.

06:34.519 --> 06:35.854
AUGUSTE: Well, let
me have my dreams.

06:35.854 --> 06:37.981
MIEP: Peter, this is for you.

06:37.981 --> 06:40.191
And, oh, Dr. Pfeffer, I wasn't
sure what you'd like,

06:40.191 --> 06:41.735
so I got you a Hesse novel.

06:41.735 --> 06:44.195
FRITZ: Oh. Thank you.
Thank you very much.

06:44.195 --> 06:47.324
MIEP: Margot, I've heard
this is a little bit racy,

06:47.324 --> 06:49.951
so I'll be borrowing it
afterwards, thank you very much.

06:49.951 --> 06:52.454
MARGOT: Miep! Thanks.

06:52.454 --> 06:53.997
PETER: I'll take
a look at that.

06:53.997 --> 06:55.081
MARGOT: Peter!
Give me that!

06:55.081 --> 06:56.249
PETER: Ooh!
Kitty Foyle!

06:56.249 --> 06:57.626
ANNE: Oh, no.
I'm gonna read that first.

06:57.626 --> 06:59.377
You haven't finished
your first book, Margot.

06:59.377 --> 07:01.087
AUGUSTE: Isn't that book
a little adult for Anne?

07:01.087 --> 07:02.839
EDITH: It's smut,
that's what it is.

07:02.839 --> 07:04.257
Nobody's reading this one.

07:04.257 --> 07:05.842
ANNE: Why?

07:05.842 --> 07:07.302
Margot might be older, but I am
more emotionally sophisticated.

07:07.302 --> 07:09.804
EDITH: Ah, conceited, Anne.

07:09.804 --> 07:11.723
ANNE: Mother,
stop being a prude!

07:11.723 --> 07:13.975
EDITH: Why does she
always contradict me?

07:13.975 --> 07:16.811
ANNE: Why would you
always treat me like a child?

07:16.811 --> 07:18.605
MIEP: Sorry, this is my fault.

07:18.605 --> 07:21.566
OTTO: No, you didn't.
It's constant now.

07:21.566 --> 07:24.319
AUGUSTE: Otto, that
girl has no boundaries.

07:24.319 --> 07:28.740
OTTO: To be fair, Anne
has nothing but boundaries.

07:30.367 --> 07:32.661
EDITH: Auguste, why don't you
tend to your child and let me

07:32.661 --> 07:36.539
tend to my child,
please, yeah?

07:36.539 --> 07:37.999
ANNE: I'm mature enough, mother.
Let me read this!

07:37.999 --> 07:39.042
(speaking German).

07:39.042 --> 07:40.126
ANNE: Mother, just let me!

07:40.126 --> 07:41.211
EDITH: Give me that book!
ANNE: No!

07:41.211 --> 07:42.253
EDITH: For you to
read this kind of.

07:42.253 --> 07:44.130
ANNE: Mother!

07:44.130 --> 07:45.840
OTTO: My God.

07:45.840 --> 07:47.634
MIEP: There was a man
waiting for you downstairs,

07:47.634 --> 07:51.054
uh, Tonny Ahlers?

07:53.223 --> 07:56.643
OTTO: What did you
say to Mr. Ahlers?

07:56.643 --> 07:58.812
MIEP: I said
you're in Switzerland.

07:58.812 --> 08:00.772
OTTO: And how did he react?

08:00.772 --> 08:03.983
MIEP: Angry, disappointed?

08:03.983 --> 08:06.486
He wanted an address,
I didn't give him anything.

08:06.486 --> 08:08.738
OTTO: Okay.

08:14.994 --> 08:17.122
MIEP: What business
do you have with him?

08:17.122 --> 08:18.373
OTTO: I don't.

08:18.373 --> 08:19.958
MIEP: Well, he said you
have a standing meeting.

08:19.958 --> 08:23.795
OTTO: Yes, we did, but I'm in
Switzerland, so now we don't.

08:26.506 --> 08:29.092
Thank you for the books.

08:34.889 --> 08:40.729
<i>♪ South of the border,
down Mexico Way ♪</i>

08:42.147 --> 08:45.775
<i>That's where I fell in love ♪</i>

08:45.775 --> 08:49.571
<i>♪ When stars above
came out to play ♪</i>

08:50.196 --> 08:56.077
<i>♪ And now as I wonder,
my thoughts ever stray ♪</i>

08:56.077 --> 08:57.871
BET: Get you something?

08:57.871 --> 09:00.790
JAN: Lager, please.

09:00.790 --> 09:02.792
<i>♪ South of the border,
down Mexico Way ♪</i>

09:02.792 --> 09:05.795
BET: You sure you're
in the right place?

09:08.173 --> 09:12.469
JAN: Uh, I'm looking for
someone named Willem Arondeus.

09:20.518 --> 09:22.687
Thank you.

09:31.863 --> 09:33.865
Willem?

09:33.865 --> 09:37.494
I, uh, I heard you
might be able to help me.

09:37.494 --> 09:42.290
I know two children whose
parents have been arrested,

09:42.290 --> 09:44.709
they're only little,
seven and five.

09:44.709 --> 09:46.878
WILLEM: Who are you?

09:46.878 --> 09:50.673
JAN: Um, sorry.

09:50.673 --> 09:53.426
My name's Jan. Jan Gies.

09:53.426 --> 09:56.513
WILLEM: No, I mean,
who are you?

09:56.513 --> 09:57.639
What do you do?

09:57.639 --> 09:59.098
What good are you to me?

09:59.098 --> 10:00.767
I'm not a social worker, okay?

10:00.767 --> 10:02.977
If I help you,
how will you help me?

10:02.977 --> 10:04.771
(chuckles)

10:04.771 --> 10:07.565
Something funny?

10:08.399 --> 10:10.985
JAN: I'm a social worker.

10:15.240 --> 10:16.533
WILLEM: They're Jewish,
these kids?

10:16.533 --> 10:17.784
JAN: Yes.

10:17.784 --> 10:20.078
Their parents were
picked up at the station.

10:20.078 --> 10:22.372
FRIEDA: We have a problem.

10:23.331 --> 10:25.875
WILLEM: Come back later.

10:30.755 --> 10:35.134
♪ ♪

10:35.134 --> 10:37.637
You, social worker!

10:37.637 --> 10:40.390
I need you.

10:50.358 --> 10:53.403
MIEP: Our company's called
Opekta, we make pectin and

10:53.403 --> 10:55.113
these spice packets.

10:55.113 --> 10:57.115
Go ahead. Taste it.

10:58.366 --> 10:59.993
It tastes like meat, right?

10:59.993 --> 11:02.245
But who can get
real meat these days?

11:02.245 --> 11:05.415
This is our special spice blend,
no one else makes it,

11:05.415 --> 11:08.376
and it makes the sausage filler
taste like real meat.

11:08.376 --> 11:10.253
Delicious, right?

11:10.253 --> 11:11.671
CUSTOMER: I'll take two,
I guess.

11:11.671 --> 11:12.797
MIEP: Oh, come on.

11:12.797 --> 11:14.507
Your wife will go
through that in a week.

11:14.507 --> 11:16.593
Unless you don't like sausage?

11:16.593 --> 11:19.429
CUSTOMER: Okay, five.

11:21.014 --> 11:23.933
MIEP: There you go.
Thank you.

11:23.933 --> 11:26.686
CUSTOMER: Thank you.

11:26.686 --> 11:28.438
JOHANNES: You really think these
tastes like real sausage?

11:28.438 --> 11:30.648
MIEP: God, no.
They're horrible.

11:30.648 --> 11:32.066
Finding anything
could help these,

11:32.066 --> 11:35.987
it's mostly ground up nutshells.

11:37.280 --> 11:39.532
JOHANNES: Ah,
it's nice to be out,

11:39.532 --> 11:41.910
not cooped up in the
office, isn't it?

11:41.910 --> 11:44.078
Think about that.

11:44.078 --> 11:46.080
A little sunlight.

11:46.080 --> 11:49.250
Moments like these make
the day seem so much nicer.

11:53.922 --> 11:56.925
And our friends
don't get to have this.

12:02.305 --> 12:06.643
MIEP: Do you ever
wonder who else is
doing what we're doing?

12:06.643 --> 12:07.936
It can't just be us, right?

12:07.936 --> 12:10.480
There must be loads of us.

12:10.480 --> 12:13.483
JOHANNES: Dear God, I hope so.

12:19.781 --> 12:24.035
MIEP: Do you know anyone
who is hiding children?

12:25.495 --> 12:28.665
JOHANNES: Yes, we are.

12:28.957 --> 12:30.291
So there shouldn't be a
sign out saying that we're

12:30.291 --> 12:33.002
available to hide anyone else.

12:33.544 --> 12:35.463
MIEP: No.
No, I don't.

12:35.463 --> 12:36.881
I'm not.

12:36.881 --> 12:38.675
JOHANNES: Good.

12:38.675 --> 12:41.678
Now let me enjoy my sunshine.

12:45.723 --> 12:47.350
FRIEDA: It's apartment 214.

12:47.350 --> 12:49.602
A Jewish family was
rounded up there this morning.

12:49.602 --> 12:50.937
WILLEM: They had to leave
behind some papers for us.

12:50.937 --> 12:52.772
A packet of important papers.

12:52.772 --> 12:54.732
FRIEDA: The Green Police are
there, a PULS moving truck

12:54.732 --> 12:56.234
will be along any minute.

12:56.234 --> 12:57.568
They'll empty the place.

12:57.568 --> 12:59.070
JAN: But if the
police are there now.

12:59.070 --> 13:01.155
WILLEM: You're a social worker,
your, your credentials

13:01.155 --> 13:03.032
can get you into
the apartment, right?

13:03.032 --> 13:04.492
You can get the package.

13:04.492 --> 13:06.035
FRIEDA: They left it in a chest
of drawers, middle drawer.

13:06.035 --> 13:07.036
WILLEM: You need to take the
package to the benches at the

13:07.036 --> 13:08.579
south end of Beatrix Park.

13:08.579 --> 13:10.540
You'll see someone there, you
will know her when you see her,

13:10.540 --> 13:11.666
just give the package to her.

13:11.666 --> 13:13.793
FRIEDA: What are you
standing here for?

13:15.003 --> 13:16.462
WILLEM: Okay.

13:16.462 --> 13:20.383
Do, do this for me and I
will help you with your kids.

13:30.059 --> 13:36.733
(bell tolling)

13:39.485 --> 13:41.529
MAN: Hurry up.

13:45.241 --> 13:50.580
(dog barking)

13:51.706 --> 13:54.333
JAN: Excuse me.
Is this for 214?

13:54.333 --> 13:55.918
POLICEMAN: What do you want?

13:55.918 --> 14:00.048
JAN: Uh, I'm here to
scout the apartment for
a non-Jewish family.

14:00.048 --> 14:01.632
Can I come in?

14:01.632 --> 14:03.801
I'll make it quick.

14:04.218 --> 14:06.471
Uh, I would've been here an hour
ago, but my bike chain broke,

14:06.471 --> 14:08.014
and my boss is
already crawling all.

14:08.014 --> 14:10.892
POLICEMAN: Fine. Just go.
And be quick.

14:10.892 --> 14:12.185
JAN: Yeah.

14:12.185 --> 14:14.604
POLICEMAN: Hurry up!
Let's go!

14:31.829 --> 14:38.544
♪ ♪

14:45.676 --> 14:52.141
♪ ♪

14:56.062 --> 14:57.855
