the whole city.

17:08.986 --> 17:10.988
MIEP: Really?
You must be so tired!

17:10.988 --> 17:14.242
MAX: Uh, They're not,
but Uncle Max is.

17:14.242 --> 17:19.413
MIEP: Hey, um, take
these and go feed pigeons.

17:19.872 --> 17:22.291
LIDDY: Come on,
Alfred, let's go.

17:26.837 --> 17:28.839
MIEP: Is it safe for
them to be outside?

17:28.839 --> 17:30.383
MAX: It's not safe for
them to be inside,

17:30.383 --> 17:32.426
it's not safe for them anywhere.

17:32.426 --> 17:33.970
I've been trying to
keep them busy all day,

17:33.970 --> 17:35.221
but they just don't stop.

17:35.221 --> 17:38.182
I, I don't know
how Frannie does it.

17:38.182 --> 17:39.350
MIEP: It's okay.

17:39.350 --> 17:42.520
MAX: No.
It's not okay.

17:43.729 --> 17:48.192
I went straight to the
Jewish Council from Mother's.

17:48.192 --> 17:52.321
Frannie and Lou were already
transported to Westerbork.

17:52.321 --> 17:56.325
But Westerbork is just a
transit camp, so from there

17:56.325 --> 17:59.370
they could be going anywhere.

18:00.371 --> 18:02.665
She's so stubborn, I told her
not to go to the train station.

18:02.665 --> 18:04.959
And now...

18:08.004 --> 18:10.673
LIDDY: Alfred, come on.

18:11.590 --> 18:15.261
MAX: They look just like
me and Frannie at that age.

18:16.304 --> 18:18.848
We used to play like that.

18:18.848 --> 18:22.018
Better than a best friend.

18:25.146 --> 18:27.565
Do you have siblings, Miep?

18:27.565 --> 18:29.900
MIEP: Yeah.
I have, I have a brother.

18:29.900 --> 18:32.862
Uh, I have a few, but
Cas and I are close.

18:32.862 --> 18:35.740
MAX: So you know.

18:36.741 --> 18:40.620
How do I keep her
children safe for her?

18:44.498 --> 18:47.168
(giggling)

18:47.960 --> 18:49.253
YOUNG MIEP: Mama please!

18:49.253 --> 18:51.464
LAURENS: Hello.
Welcome to Amsterdam.

18:51.464 --> 18:54.425
I'm your new papa
temporary papa.

18:54.425 --> 18:57.011
Boys, everyone,
slow down, slow down.

18:57.011 --> 18:59.347
Hermine doesn't know Dutch.

18:59.347 --> 19:00.973
She only speaks German.

19:00.973 --> 19:02.558
Cas, can you help?

19:02.558 --> 19:04.477
GENOFEVA: You speak German.

19:20.284 --> 19:22.244
(laughing)

19:22.244 --> 19:23.829
GENOFEVA: Cas,
what is she saying?

19:23.829 --> 19:26.957
YOUNG CAS: She says I can
speak German really well,

19:26.957 --> 19:29.210
and that she's hungry.

19:29.210 --> 19:30.878
GENOFEVA: Well,
we can fix that.

19:30.878 --> 19:32.254
Boys, come on.
Off to the kitchen.

19:32.254 --> 19:34.757
Let's make some sandwiches.

19:51.023 --> 19:55.361
MIEP: Max, I might
know a family.

19:55.361 --> 19:58.447
They, they take,
they've taken in kids before.

19:58.447 --> 19:59.740
MAX: Really?

19:59.740 --> 20:01.117
MIEP: Well, they've
taken in a kid before.

20:01.117 --> 20:02.993
They took in me.

20:02.993 --> 20:05.663
I'll speak to them.

20:09.625 --> 20:11.585
GENOFEVA: Look who's here?
LAURENS: Hey, there she is.

20:11.585 --> 20:13.087
MIEP: Hey.

20:13.087 --> 20:14.213
LAURENS: What's going on?
Are you joining us for dinner?

20:14.213 --> 20:16.090
MIEP: No, I can't.
I don't have much time.

20:16.090 --> 20:19.718
GENOFEVA: She's got
something important she
wants to talk to us about.

20:20.344 --> 20:23.431
Oh, wait, she's pregnant.

20:23.431 --> 20:25.433
LAURENS: Are you pregnant?

20:25.433 --> 20:26.809
GENOFEVA: Please tell
me you're pregnant.

20:26.809 --> 20:28.144
MIEP: I'm not pregnant.

20:28.144 --> 20:29.603
CAS: Who's pregnant?
MIEP: No, no one's pregnant.

20:29.603 --> 20:31.480
LAURENS: Miep.
MIEP: No one's pregnant.

20:31.480 --> 20:33.441
GENOFEVA: So what
did you want to say?

20:33.441 --> 20:36.444
MIEP: Oh, I'll
tell you in a second.

20:36.444 --> 20:37.570
Hello.

20:37.570 --> 20:38.988
CAS: Hi.

20:38.988 --> 20:41.866
MIEP: Are you okay?
CAS: Uh-hmm.

20:59.216 --> 21:00.843
GENOFEVA: No German, you two.

21:29.830 --> 21:30.915
LAURENS: Enough German.

21:30.915 --> 21:33.031
Miep, what did you
wanna talk about?

21:36.837 --> 21:42.426
(baby crying)

21:44.261 --> 21:49.266
(baby quiets)

21:49.266 --> 21:54.104
JAN: Oh, you like that?

21:54.104 --> 21:56.649
(laughing)

21:56.649 --> 21:59.985
You like that? Yeah?

22:04.114 --> 22:07.117
WOMAN: Hi, darling.
Hi, how was your day?

22:17.211 --> 22:20.381
Thank you.

22:23.050 --> 22:27.346
JAN: Wait, so, he likes this.

22:45.489 --> 22:49.118
MIEP: You have to be careful.
CAS: I know.

22:49.118 --> 22:51.036
MIEP: No.
I, I mean you have to.

22:51.036 --> 22:52.663
CAS: I am.

22:52.663 --> 22:56.000
MIEP: Can you just
not be a homosexual?

22:56.000 --> 22:58.878
CAS: Ha.

22:58.878 --> 23:01.672
MIEP: I'm kind of not joking.

23:03.757 --> 23:04.884
CAS: You should be.

23:04.884 --> 23:06.302
MIEP: Just until
the war is over?

23:06.302 --> 23:08.637
Just don't see
anyone or be with anyone.

23:08.637 --> 23:11.140
CAS: It's not just
something that I do, Miep.

23:11.140 --> 23:14.810
MIEP: I know, I know, but
people are making sacrifices

23:14.810 --> 23:16.395
all over to stay safe.

23:16.395 --> 23:17.521
CAS: Uh-hmm. Uh-hmm.

23:17.521 --> 23:18.772
MIEP: People are
going underground,

23:18.772 --> 23:20.733
people are going into hiding.

23:20.733 --> 23:24.153
Can you not just hide
one part of yourself?

23:24.153 --> 23:26.947
CAS: Miep, I, I know how
to hide a part of myself.

23:26.947 --> 23:29.491
I've been doing
it all my life.

23:29.491 --> 23:31.619
You have no idea what it's
like to walk around every day

23:31.619 --> 23:33.495
with this giant secret.

23:33.495 --> 23:37.708
And, and, and lie in the
faces of people that
you love every day.

23:39.585 --> 23:43.380
So please just don't
tell me how to do this.

23:45.507 --> 23:46.884
MIEP: Okay.

23:46.884 --> 23:50.346
I'm gonna leave before I
say something I shouldn't.

23:53.724 --> 23:55.392
CAS: Are you ashamed of me?

23:55.392 --> 23:57.061
MIEP: How can you ask me that?

23:57.061 --> 23:58.896
CAS: Because
something's changed.

23:58.896 --> 24:00.439
You're, you're
being really weird.

24:00.439 --> 24:03.150
You're distant, and
you always have to go.

24:03.984 --> 24:06.570
I miss you.

24:07.112 --> 24:09.615
MIEP: Nothing's changed.
CAS: No, you're lying.

24:09.615 --> 24:12.159
And we don't lie to
each other remember?

24:12.159 --> 24:13.619
You got this, this look
where you can't look,

24:13.619 --> 24:15.454
you're doing it now, you
can't look me in the eye.

24:15.454 --> 24:17.414
MIEP: No. I'm not.

24:37.184 --> 24:42.773
♪ ♪

24:42.773 --> 24:49.571
<i>♪ I don't want to
set the world on fire ♪</i>

24:52.408 --> 24:57.871
<i>♪ I just want to start a flame ♪</i>

24:57.871 --> 25:00.874
JAN: I need to speak to you.
MAN: Who is he?

25:00.874 --> 25:03.377
WILLEM: Can, can we
have a minute, please?

25:03.377 --> 25:05.212
Just.

25:05.212 --> 25:11.760
<i>♪ In my heart,
I have but one desire ♪</i>

25:13.345 --> 25:14.638
WILLEM: I heard you got it.

25:14.638 --> 25:17.016
JAN: Papers!
A packet of papers!

25:17.016 --> 25:18.851
Why the hell
didn't you tell me?

25:18.851 --> 25:21.103
WILLEM: You might have
hesitated, we didn't have time.

25:21.103 --> 25:23.355
JAN: Hesitated?
You damn right I hesitated.

25:23.355 --> 25:24.606
What if I'd panicked?

25:24.606 --> 25:26.900
What if, what if
I'd left it there?

25:26.900 --> 25:28.902
WILLEM: Then you'd
be a monster.

25:28.902 --> 25:32.740
And I'd be bad at reading
people, which I am not.

25:32.740 --> 25:36.410
JAN: That's great.
That, that's fantastic.

25:37.995 --> 25:40.748
Oh my God.

25:40.748 --> 25:43.000
Sorry.

25:47.046 --> 25:50.549
So who was the
girl in the park?

25:50.549 --> 25:52.217
WILLEM: Does it matter?

25:52.217 --> 25:55.012
They're people.

25:55.554 --> 25:58.807
Really grateful people.

26:00.058 --> 26:02.978
I'm grateful, too.

26:07.566 --> 26:09.651
On here is the address
of a student at the

26:09.651 --> 26:12.362
University of Amsterdam.

26:12.362 --> 26:14.448
He's got a group that's hiding
Jewish children with families

26:14.448 --> 26:16.909
in the countryside.

26:18.160 --> 26:21.205
JAN: Thank you.
Thank you.

26:36.303 --> 26:39.598
Miep. Miep.

26:46.313 --> 26:50.442
MIEP: They asked.
I was too tired to say no.

26:51.527 --> 26:53.487
You're home late.

26:53.487 --> 26:55.114
Work?

26:55.114 --> 26:57.449
JAN: Yeah.

26:58.742 --> 27:01.495
MIEP: You're up early,
you're out late.

27:01.495 --> 27:04.623
JAN: It's a busy time.

27:09.253 --> 27:13.257
MIEP: I have to
tell you something.

27:17.052 --> 27:20.055
I know we said that we weren't
gonna try to hide the kids.

27:20.055 --> 27:22.432
But I couldn't help it, and I
went to my parents' house to

27:22.432 --> 27:24.685
see if they would take them
in like they did with me.

27:24.685 --> 27:26.270
JAN: What did they say?

27:26.270 --> 27:27.771
MIEP: Well, I couldn't bring
myself to do it because it

27:27.771 --> 27:31.316
would put my parents
in so much danger.

27:31.316 --> 27:34.069
And Cas already has
a target on his back.

27:34.069 --> 27:36.154
And it would make it
more dangerous for him,

27:36.154 --> 27:37.823
and more dangerous for us.

27:37.823 --> 27:40.075
And I really don't
wanna lose my brother.

27:40.075 --> 27:42.327
But, look at them, like,

27:42.327 --> 27:45.372
they're just little kids
and who am I to decide.

27:45.372 --> 27:48.667
JAN: Shh. It's okay.
It's okay. It's okay.

27:48.667 --> 27:51.879
MIEP: Why are you smiling?

27:52.421 --> 27:55.507
JAN: I found a place for them.

27:55.507 --> 27:58.969
MIEP: Really?
JAN: Yeah.

28:02.764 --> 28:04.057
(chuckling)

28:04.057 --> 28:05.851
(shushing)

28:08.312 --> 28:11.732
MRS. STOPPELMAN: They're
college students and are
they taking my grandbabies?

28:11.732 --> 28:13.025
JAN: No, no, no.

28:13.025 --> 28:14.735
They just relocate them.

28:14.735 --> 28:17.654
They'll take them to a nice
family in the countryside.

28:17.654 --> 28:20.616
But they said they
have to go tonight.

28:20.616 --> 28:23.160
So Miep and I will take them.

28:23.160 --> 28:24.578
MRS. STOPPELMAN: Why
are you taking them?

28:24.578 --> 28:25.913
MAX: Because you're
a mess, mother,

28:25.913 --> 28:27.873
and it has to happen
quickly and quietly.

28:27.873 --> 28:29.249
MRS. STOPPELMAN: No. No.

28:29.249 --> 28:31.251
JAN: You, you can say
your goodbyes here.

28:31.251 --> 28:33.587
And we'll make sure they
get there safe and sound.

28:33.587 --> 28:36.465
If you'll agree to it.

28:36.465 --> 28:39.134
MRS. STOPPELMAN: It's too quick,
it's too sudden.

28:39.134 --> 28:41.887
MAX: Mother, Jan and Miep
have it all arranged.

28:41.887 --> 28:44.932
We have to trust them.

28:49.853 --> 28:51.271
JAN: Okay, good.

28:51.271 --> 28:53.273
I'll make the arrangements.

28:53.273 --> 28:56.568
MIEP: Mrs. Stoppelman,
do you have any peroxide?

28:57.277 --> 28:58.862
MRS. STOPPELMAN: Why?

28:58.862 --> 29:01.031
MIEP: We have to dye
the children's hair.

29:01.031 --> 29:01.867
MRS. STOPPELMAN: Oh.

29:12.542 --> 29:14.086
MIEP: You all right?
ANNE: No.

29:14.086 --> 29:16.713
MIEP: What is it?
ANNE: Her.

29:16.713 --> 29:18.382
MIEP: You're still angry
that she took that book?

29:18.382 --> 29:20.509
ANNE: I'm angry that I have a
mother who is mean, and wants

29:20.509 --> 29:23.261
me to know as little
about the world as she does.

29:23.261 --> 29:24.888
MIEP: Anne, you have to
stop fighting with her,

29:24.888 --> 29:26.556
the whole neighborhood
can hear you.

29:26.556 --> 29:28.392
And move, the office is
opening in half an hour.

29:28.392 --> 29:29.518
I have to get these upstairs.

29:29.518 --> 29:32.270
ANNE: No, I'll help.
I'll take them.

29:32.270 --> 29:33.855
MIEP: There you go.

29:33.855 --> 29:36.316
Hey, if you wanna be helpful,
stop fighting with your mother.

29:36.316 --> 29:38.527
ANNE: Tell her that.

29:45.033 --> 29:49.121
JOHANNES: Miep, this man is
from the Dutch Nazi Party.

29:50.038 --> 29:53.625
TONNY: You, hello again.

29:54.918 --> 29:57.796
Your friends here are
telling me the same story

29:57.796 --> 30:00.215
you did yesterday.

30:00.215 --> 30:02.676
Tell me where I
can find Otto Frank.

30:02.676 --> 30:04.094
It's urgent I reach him.

30:04.094 --> 30:06.388
We have a business partnership,
and he has abandoned it.

30:06.388 --> 30:08.473
MIEP: What
business partnership?

30:08.473 --> 30:10.350
And what monthly meeting?

30:10.350 --> 30:12.686
I've worked here for years,
and I've never heard of you.

30:12.686 --> 30:14.271
Have you?

30:14.271 --> 30:16.523
I'm sorry, I'm just trying to
understand, so, so I can help.

30:16.523 --> 30:18.567
TONNY: Well, someone
must know where he is.

30:18.567 --> 30:20.485
MIEP: Like I said yesterday,
I have absolutely no idea

30:20.485 --> 30:22.279
where he's gone.

30:22.279 --> 30:24.948
Sorry.

30:24.948 --> 30:27.993
TONNY: One of you.

30:30.662 --> 30:33.957
All right.
Give me your names.

30:33.957 --> 30:36.918
MIEP: Is that necessary?

30:36.918 --> 30:39.796
TONNY: Starting with you.

30:41.048 --> 30:42.632
MIEP: He took
down all our names.

30:42.632 --> 30:44.468
OTTO: He's just
trying to scare you.

30:44.468 --> 30:47.054
MIEP: We don't know
what he plans to do.

30:47.054 --> 30:49.723
He's NSB, he's a Dutch Nazi,

30:49.723 --> 30:52.809
so you have a
partnership with a Nazi.

30:55.854 --> 30:58.857
Sir.

30:58.857 --> 31:00.901
Mr. Frank, we can't
have secrets,

31:00.901 --> 31:03.320
especially not about
things like this.

31:03.320 --> 31:06.615
And if I'm the one downstairs,
I have to be...

31:09.076 --> 31:12.788
that's a pretty good secret.

31:16.917 --> 31:18.210
Oh, no.

31:18.210 --> 31:20.837
OTTO: It's all right.
MIEP: No, thank you. Okay.

31:28.261 --> 31:30.430
OTTO: Edith doesn't know
what I'm going to tell you,

31:30.430 --> 31:33.558
certainly not the girls.

31:34.101 --> 31:35.936
About a year ago,
I was talking to a supplier

31:35.936 --> 31:38.730
at a trade show.

31:38.730 --> 31:43.026
I should have known better but
I was talking about the war.

31:43.860 --> 31:46.196
I told him it will end soon.

31:46.196 --> 31:49.282
And when it does, it won't
end well for the Nazis.

31:49.282 --> 31:51.618
MIEP: Oh.

31:53.328 --> 31:55.831
OTTO: Of course this man
who was a collaborator,

31:55.831 --> 31:58.792
and a good one, he wrote a
letter to the Nazi party

31:58.792 --> 32:00.752
telling them what I said.

32:00.752 --> 32:02.712
And I would have been arrested,

32:02.712 --> 32:07.008
if it weren't for an
enterprising NSB messenger.

32:07.008 --> 32:08.635
MIEP: Tonny Ahlers.

32:08.635 --> 32:10.428
OTTO: Ahlers intercepted the
letter and told me that if

32:10.428 --> 32:14.683
I didn't pay him, he
would give it to the Nazis.

32:14.683 --> 32:16.685
MIEP: So this
"business partnership?"

32:16.685 --> 32:19.563
OTTO: Blackmail.
Pure and simple.

32:19.563 --> 32:21.690
Which would have fine,
before, but now.

32:21.690 --> 32:24.025
MIEP: He thinks
you're in Switzerland.

32:24.025 --> 32:27.195
OTTO: He heard
I'm in Switzerland.

32:28.321 --> 32:31.616
He's ignorant and venal,
Miep, but he's not stupid.

32:31.616 --> 32:34.077
He knows people are hiding.

32:34.077 --> 32:38.331
He's like a dog sniffing
around for a bone.

32:38.331 --> 32:41.209
He won't stop.

32:44.921 --> 32:48.800
And now they're
murdering us by the thousands.

32:49.801 --> 32:53.096
Making piles of us.

32:57.142 --> 32:59.728
I thought we were safe.

32:59.728 --> 33:01.938
I planned so carefully.

33:01.938 --> 33:05.150
Furniture, supplies and
food, piece by piece.

33:05.150 --> 33:07.277
Bit by bit.

33:07.277 --> 33:10.739
I made a paper trail all
the way to Switzerland.

33:11.740 --> 33:14.784
They were safe,
Edith and the girls,

33:14.784 --> 33:18.622
I had them in a safe place.

33:18.622 --> 33:22.667
One sentence and then,
I don't even remember saying

33:22.667 --> 33:24.127
and I failed them.

33:24.127 --> 33:25.337
MIEP: Okay. No. Stop.

33:25.337 --> 33:27.505
Sorry, I can't listen to this.

33:27.505 --> 33:30.425
So you couldn't keep
your mouth shut once?

33:30.425 --> 33:33.720
I'm the Crown Princess
of not being able to
keep her mouth shut.

33:34.971 --> 33:37.766
This is not your fault.

33:38.183 --> 33:39.851
OTTO: It's different.
MIEP: No.

33:39.851 --> 33:42.229
When your family were in
trouble, you moved heaven and

33:42.229 --> 33:44.689
earth for them, you
moved them across Europe.

33:44.689 --> 33:46.650
You built them a fortress.

33:46.650 --> 33:50.362
No one in the world has kept his
children safer than you have.

33:51.780 --> 33:56.409
Mr. Frank, you are the
finest father I've ever met.

33:58.703 --> 34:01.581
And don't worry
about Tonny Ahlers.

34:01.581 --> 34:02.749
He's nothing.

34:02.749 --> 34:05.543
We'll scrape him off our shoe.

34:06.044 --> 34:10.674
(muffled fighting)

34:11.216 --> 34:12.801
OTTO: These two.

34:12.801 --> 34:15.095
MIEP: Oh, she is 13.

34:15.095 --> 34:16.846
OTTO: Yeah, It's true.

34:16.846 --> 34:19.474
It's natural.

34:19.474 --> 34:21.476
She's growing apart
from her mother,

34:21.476 --> 34:24.729
which makes Edith hold her
more tightly and Anne...

34:24.729 --> 34:26.147
MIEP: Fights her harder.

34:26.147 --> 34:28.441
OTTO: Tooth and nail.

34:30.568 --> 34:33.405
Most families, they
would just make little
space for each other.

34:33.405 --> 34:36.449
But for us it's impossible.

34:37.409 --> 34:41.496
Another problem
I didn't foresee.

34:42.998 --> 34:45.834
You'll understand when
you have a daughter.

34:47.627 --> 34:51.881
(train whistle)

34:54.718 --> 34:59.139
(train announcements).

35:14.321 --> 35:16.573
YOUNG MIEP: Mama, please!

35:22.537 --> 35:25.540
ALFRED: I look silly!
Jan, look at my hair.

35:25.540 --> 35:27.626
MIEP: All right. Come.
LIDDY: No, I don't want it!

35:27.626 --> 35:29.210
MIEP: Oh, come on.
LIDDY: I don't want it.

35:29.210 --> 35:30.462
MIEP: Alfred did it.
LIDDY: You can't make me.

35:30.462 --> 35:31.713
MIEP: And he's a baby.
LIDDY: I won't.

35:31.713 --> 35:32.881
MIEP: And he's a boy.
LIDDY: No. Please no.

35:32.881 --> 35:34.299
MIEP: Don't worry,
it will grow back.

35:34.299 --> 35:36.801
LIDDY: No.
Where are we going?

35:36.801 --> 35:39.638
Why can't we stay with you?

35:39.888 --> 35:42.140
MIEP: All right.

35:42.140 --> 35:45.143
I'm going to
tell you something.

35:45.810 --> 35:49.022
When I was a little girl,
I went on a train,

35:49.022 --> 35:52.484
all by myself and I had
no idea where I was going.

35:52.484 --> 35:56.571
And I was, I was really, really
scared just like you are.

35:56.571 --> 35:59.824
LIDDY: Why did
they send you away?

35:59.824 --> 36:03.495
MIEP: Because my
mother had no choice.

36:03.495 --> 36:06.915
I wasn't very well
and I was in trouble,

36:06.915 --> 36:09.918
and I needed help or
I was going to die.

36:10.543 --> 36:14.381
LIDDY: Are we in trouble?

36:15.090 --> 36:18.259
MIEP: Yes.

36:21.221 --> 36:23.973
LIDDY: Where did you go?

36:23.973 --> 36:28.103
MIEP: Oh, well, I went to a
family who could take care of me

36:28.103 --> 36:29.604
and give the help I needed.

36:29.604 --> 36:31.356
And they did.

36:31.356 --> 36:33.316
LIDDY: And then you went home?

36:33.316 --> 36:34.984
MIEP: No, actually.

36:34.984 --> 36:39.489
I loved it so much that I stayed
and it became my new home.

36:40.657 --> 36:42.450
LIDDY: You loved it?

36:42.450 --> 36:46.246
MIEP: I loved it.
It was really fun.

36:46.246 --> 36:51.167
And you know when I did
that I was all on my own,

36:51.167 --> 36:54.129
but you have Alfred.

36:54.796 --> 36:57.590
You have your brother and as
long as you have your brother,

36:57.590 --> 36:59.551
you'll be okay.

36:59.551 --> 37:02.303
You'll be safe.

37:02.929 --> 37:05.014
All right? Okay.

37:05.014 --> 37:07.350
In you go.
Brave girl.

37:07.350 --> 37:09.936
All right.
Let's do it.

37:11.938 --> 37:15.233
You okay?

37:20.613 --> 37:24.784
Ready?

37:25.368 --> 37:27.370
Okay.

37:29.330 --> 37:32.000
MAX: Be brave.

37:33.752 --> 37:35.754
MRS. STOPPELMAN:
Now, children.

37:35.754 --> 37:36.921
Listen to me.

37:36.921 --> 37:39.591
I've got something
very important to say.

37:40.675 --> 37:43.219
It doesn't matter what
color your hair is,

37:43.219 --> 37:45.430
or what name people call you.

37:45.430 --> 37:49.058
You are you mother's
children and you are
your father's children.

37:49.058 --> 37:51.644
You are my
grandchildren always.

37:51.644 --> 37:55.732
Now, where you're going, you
might be asked to do things

37:55.732 --> 37:58.735
that we've said
you must never do.

37:58.735 --> 38:03.198
To steal or lie or to eat
foods that are not kosher.

38:03.198 --> 38:07.786
And you're good children
you will say, "Oma said no!"

38:07.786 --> 38:12.957
But the most important
commandment in Judaism

38:12.957 --> 38:15.710
is to preserve life.

38:15.710 --> 38:19.339
You have to live and you
must do what you must.

38:19.339 --> 38:21.674
And Oma will understand.

38:21.674 --> 38:24.469
And Oma will always love you.

38:24.469 --> 38:27.847
Always.

38:27.847 --> 38:29.599
LIDDY: Yes, Oma.

38:29.599 --> 38:31.459
(crying)

38:33.228 --> 38:35.021
MIEP: Who
arranged all of this?

38:35.021 --> 38:37.607
JAN: I don't know.
Some people knew some people.

38:37.607 --> 38:40.944
If you just stay here.

38:42.403 --> 38:44.113
ALFRED: We're
going in the car?

38:44.113 --> 38:45.448
MIEP: We're going in a car? How?

38:45.448 --> 38:46.991
JAN: This is what
they said to do!

38:46.991 --> 38:48.243
In you get.

38:48.243 --> 38:51.037
MIEP: Wait, who is "they?"
JAN: Quick, quick.

39:03.925 --> 39:10.515
♪ ♪

39:15.311 --> 39:19.065
We're here.

39:38.543 --> 39:41.421
We're early.

39:48.886 --> 39:52.432
MIEP: They're finally asleep.

39:55.643 --> 39:59.898
Where are they taking them?

39:59.898 --> 40:03.818
JAN: I don't know.
MIEP: Jan what?

40:04.319 --> 40:07.488
Some "people" are taking
them to "I don't know?"

40:07.488 --> 40:09.073
Who are they?

40:09.073 --> 40:11.409
Where are they going,
what if Liddy needs something?

40:11.409 --> 40:12.952
How are we going
to get them back?

40:12.952 --> 40:14.454
JAN: We don't get to know.

40:14.454 --> 40:15.788
MIEP: What? Why?

40:15.788 --> 40:20.376
JAN: Because if one day
we get caught,

40:20.376 --> 40:23.087
and they put a gun to
your head and say to me,

40:23.087 --> 40:25.965
"Tell us where the Jews are
or we'll kill your wife,"

40:25.965 --> 40:28.176
I won't be able to tell them.

40:28.176 --> 40:31.179
Because I won't know.

40:38.603 --> 40:42.857
MIEP: Why is the gun
to my head, not yours?

40:42.857 --> 40:45.485
Why aren't they asking
me where the Jews are?

40:45.485 --> 40:49.364
(laughing)

40:50.657 --> 40:52.533
JAN: Because you're prettier.
That's why.

40:52.533 --> 40:56.788
MIEP: Oh, yes.

40:56.788 --> 40:59.999
(engine rumbling)

40:59.999 --> 41:02.960
JAN: Something's out there.

41:04.504 --> 41:08.007
MIEP: Alfred, Liddy, wake up.

41:17.558 --> 41:24.273
♪ ♪

41:25.942 --> 41:28.277
JAN: Okay.
This is it.

41:36.327 --> 41:40.540
MIEP: Come on, Alfred.
JAN: Come on, come on.

41:47.588 --> 41:53.469
♪ ♪

41:54.137 --> 41:56.514
STUDENT: What are their names?

41:56.514 --> 41:59.267
MIEP: This is Liddy
and this is Alfred.

42:00.226 --> 42:03.354
STUDENT: Hi, Liddy.
Hi, Alfred.

42:08.568 --> 42:10.611
JAN: So what do we do?

42:10.611 --> 42:14.073
STUDENT: Just wait a minute.

42:14.824 --> 42:15.992
JAN: Go. Go.

42:15.992 --> 42:19.162
STUDENT: Stop.
It's okay. She's with us.

42:22.707 --> 42:25.626
I'm gonna take the boy and
she's going to take the girl.

42:25.626 --> 42:27.253
MIEP: No, you know
they're going together.

42:27.253 --> 42:28.838
You said they
wouldn't be separated.

42:28.838 --> 42:30.214
JAN: Oh, I didn't know.

42:30.214 --> 42:31.758
STUDENT: No family is taking
on two kids and it's a

42:31.758 --> 42:33.092
dead giveaway to the Nazis.

42:33.092 --> 42:34.135
MIEP: They have
to stay together.

42:34.135 --> 42:35.344
She needs her brother.

42:35.344 --> 42:36.804
STUDENT: No.
We have to split them up.

42:36.804 --> 42:38.431
MIEP: No.
Never mind then.

42:38.431 --> 42:39.807
I'll take them.
Come on children.

42:39.807 --> 42:41.184
STUDENT: This is
no good, let's go.

42:41.184 --> 42:42.268
JAN: No, no, no, no.
Wait, wait, wait, wait, wait.

42:42.268 --> 42:44.854
Please wait. Wait.

42:45.563 --> 42:50.610
Miep, this is
how it has to be.

42:50.610 --> 42:54.572
You know it is.

42:54.572 --> 42:56.574
This is their chance.

42:56.574 --> 42:58.743
This is their
only chance, okay?

42:58.743 --> 43:00.161
Okay. Okay.

43:00.161 --> 43:03.498
Come on.
Come on.

43:06.501 --> 43:09.921
This is Alfred.

43:09.921 --> 43:12.048
This is Liddy.

43:25.686 --> 43:27.480
(train whistle)

43:48.543 --> 43:52.004
♪ ♪

43:52.004 --> 43:54.674
MIEP: Liddy, Alfred,
come here.

43:54.674 --> 43:55.883
Listen to me.

43:55.883 --> 43:58.845
You're going to a
good place, both of you.

43:58.845 --> 44:03.057
Both of you are.
You'll be safe.

44:03.766 --> 44:06.894
You'll be okay.
You'll both be okay.

44:07.979 --> 44:13.234
LIDDY: Like you.
MIEP: Yes. Yes.

44:13.568 --> 44:16.028
Like me.

44:17.113 --> 44:22.034
Come.

44:23.619 --> 44:24.996
Okay.

44:24.996 --> 44:27.999
Off you go.
Off you go.

44:32.461 --> 44:39.176
♪ ♪

44:53.190 --> 44:59.322
♪ ♪

44:59.322 --> 45:03.200
Anne, good morning.

45:06.204 --> 45:07.788
ANNE: What's wrong?

45:07.788 --> 45:09.624
MIEP: Oh, nothing. Nothing.

45:09.624 --> 45:13.461
It's almost time to wake up
and I needed to talk to you.

45:18.549 --> 45:20.760
Anne...

45:22.845 --> 45:27.892
Please try to see your
mother a little differently.

45:29.143 --> 45:33.105
Try to think about not
what she does, but why.

45:35.024 --> 45:39.111
She just wants to
keep you alive and safe.

45:39.111 --> 45:41.530
And that might mean keeping
you her little girl,

45:41.530 --> 45:44.325
for a bit longer,

45:45.284 --> 45:51.415
but she loves you so much.

45:54.543 --> 45:57.380
More than you could know.

45:59.799 --> 46:02.593
ANNE: Okay.

46:08.349 --> 46:14.689
♪ ♪

46:21.404 --> 46:25.574
♪ ♪

46:25.574 --> 46:32.081
<i>♪ I don't want to
set the world on fire ♪</i>

46:35.793 --> 46:39.505
<i>♪ I just want to start ♪</i>

46:39.505 --> 46:44.552
<i>♪ A flame in your heart ♪</i>

46:46.762 --> 46:48.848
<i>♪ In my heart ♪</i>

46:48.848 --> 46:54.687
<i>♪ I have but one desire ♪</i>

46:56.480 --> 47:01.068
<i>♪ And that one is you ♪</i>

47:01.068 --> 47:05.906
<i>♪ No other will do ♪</i>

47:08.117 --> 47:13.581
<i>♪ I've lost all ambition
for worldly acclaim ♪</i>

47:13.581 --> 47:18.753
<i>♪ I just want to be
the one you love ♪</i>

47:18.753 --> 47:21.338
<i>And with your admission ♪</i>

47:21.338 --> 47:24.425
<i>♪ That you feel the same ♪</i>

47:24.425 --> 47:29.972
<i>♪ I'll have reached the goal
I'm dreaming of believe me ♪</i>

47:29.972 --> 47:36.479
<i>♪ I don't want to set
the world on fire ♪</i>
